But labeling commenters as trolls, spammers, or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed a group of people that Hogan had blocked on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to have a conversation with their elected leaders, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs, pastors, for example.
They told me that their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and appropriate.
