Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink heavily.
"No one dares to walk in the village after five in the evening", says Degei.
This is a rare foray into the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote in public in front of occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed the Dutch occupation, quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which has kept the area under tight control and barred access to foreign journalists and human rights observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the eastern part of the island belonging to Papua New Guinea.
The remote and rugged Enarotali is reached by a flight of an hour and a half from the provincial capital, Jayapura, to Nabire, followed by a five-hour, stomach-churning ride in a rented car.
There's no public transportation here.
The town of some 19,000 inhabitants has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo groves, whose waves have rusted the roofs to a brilliant blue.
Only a few Indonesians have been here, let alone journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the tribes of the Mee Pago in Papua worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We didn't have clothes like this", says Degei, referring to her colorful, hand-woven turban, dark lace and bright-colored sweater.
Before we had nothing but leaves to cover our bodies.
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28 percent of its population living below the poverty line and one of the highest rates of child mortality and illiteracy in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold.
Paniai is a highland area roughly the size of New Jersey, with a population of 153,000. Only about a hundred miles from Paniai is Grasberg, the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, owned by the Freeport McMoran Company, based in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine produced $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in timber reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, for they mean the oppressive presence of a strong Indonesian military.
The New York Times revealed in 2005 that Freeport paid local military personnel and local units of the military nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, with individual officers paid as much as $150,000.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten this source of income, and they are mercilessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969 the Indonesian military has killed more than 500,000 Papuans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands more.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the mass killings of the highland tribes in Papua in the 1970s amounted to genocide.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the region for peaceful protests.
The Archdiocese of Brisbane's 2016 report We Will Lose Everything contains accounts of the atrocities of the previous year, including extrajudicial executions, torture  rape and electrocution are particularly popular methods  and ruthless attacks on peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to count the number of victims because there are cases every week", says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The situation has tightened as Papua's natural resources attract migrants from elsewhere in Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, 83 percent are Christians, but the demographics are changing as Muslims from the populous Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra, and Sulawesi move into the area in hopes of a better livelihood.
