Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may alleviate irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate might sound like a digestive nightmare.
However, recent research suggests the opposite: A diet high in meat protein and dairy products may alleviate irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is a chronic disease that affects some 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, and it causes stomach cramps, bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although people with IBS are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan, found in the protein, helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen the intestinal tolerance.
According to the director of the study, Marco Colonna, immune cells guard the gut and prevent harmful microbes lurking in food from entering the body.
The cells that cause inflammation are balanced by the cells that promote resistance, which protect the body without damaging the delicate tissues.
If the balance falls too close to the inflammation, the result can be irritable bowel syndrome.
In experiments, immune cells that promote tolerance were found in mice that had a specific bacterium in their intestines.
Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins, and it is needed by the bacteria to make immune cells.
'We found a link between Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of resistance-promoting cells, which are part of the normal gut microbiome,' says Professor Colonna.
 The more tryptophan the mice ate, the more these immune cells were present. 
If the same effect is observed in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan may enhance intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammatory susceptibility.
In her study of immune-boosting cells, researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that, while one group of mice had such cells, the same mice kept in isolation did not.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiome of the mice, the normal community of bacteria, fungi, and viruses in the digestive tract.
When they examined the gut DNA of the mice, they found six different types of bacteria that were present in the mice with immune cells, but not in the other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice that had grown up in a sterile environment, but had no gut microbiome and had not developed immune cells, the immune cells started to appear.
To find out how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in a liquid and transferred small amounts of liquid - free of bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells evolved into cells that enhance tolerance.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of resistance-enhancing cells increased by about 50 percent; when the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells dropped by half.
Cervantes-Barragan says that humans have the same immune-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan by-products from Lactobacillus reuteri cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice, but there have been some cases of tryptophan-related genetic defects in patients with acute myeloid leukaemia.
'We probably want to encourage the development of these cells, because they regulate inflammation in the intestinal lining,' says Cervantes-Barragan.
 High levels of tryptophan in combination with Lactobacillus reuteri may contribute to their proliferation.
